article.headline: Turnovers kill Minnesota
article.linkText: Taurasi scores 18 as Mercury declaw Lynx
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- The Phoenix Mercury took advantage of 22
turnovers by the Minnesota Lynx and earned just their second win in
six games.

Diana Taurasi scored 11 of her 18 points in a 19-5 run early in
the second half, and the Mercury beat the Lynx 69-46 Tuesday night.

"We definitely knew we had to put two halves together," said
the Mercury's Penny Taylor, who added 17 points and seven rebounds
after being gone a week preparing for the Olympics with the
Australian national team. "We've had games in the past where we've
had a great first half or a great second half."

In their first meeting, June 5 in Minneapolis, the Lynx overcame
a 14-point deficit to beat the Mercury 76-68.

On Tuesday night, Phoenix scored 27 points Minnesota turnovers.
The Lynx lost for the third time in four games.

"It's been a thorn in our side the whole season so far,"
Minnesota coach Suzie McConnell Serio said. "We are averaging too
many turnovers (18.7 a game, tops in the league) and teams are
capitalizing. So it's something we need to continue to address and
try and find an answer."

Normally, the answer is Katie Smith, the league's fourth-leading
scorer at 18.3 points a game. But she was held scoreless in the
first half and finished with eight points on 3-of-10 shooting.

"Too many turnovers again, that's something that's a constant
for us," Smith said. "Something that has been hurting us every
single game. It was not a very happy night for any of us."

Her first basket, a layup with 18:08 left, cut the lead to
31-29. But Phoenix went on its big run, making six of eight shots
at one stretch to go up by 16 points.

"I believe that is the best game we've played defensively,"
Phoenix coach Carrie Graf said. "We forced 22 turnovers, we had 16
steals, and to hold Katie Smith to eight points is a hell of a team
effort. We mixed up some things that we did with her. It was a
great team effort."

Vanessa Hayden led the Lynx with 10 points. Nicole Ohlde was
held to five points, six under her average, and seven rebounds.

Taurasi, fifth in the league in scoring at 18.2 points a game,
made five of seven shots in the second half and added five rebounds
and two assists.

Adrian Williams scored all nine of her points in the first half
to lead Phoenix to a 29-25 lead.

Phoenix took advantage of five quick Minnesota turnovers in the
first six minutes for a 13-4 lead. But the Mercury missed five
straight shots to allow Minnesota to get its first lead at 24-23
with 2:41 left then scored six of the last seven points of the
half.
